lthough framed as objective “archival” truths, these histories were meant to erase or marginalize the powerful and persistent affective appropriations of the monuments by groups who often existed outside the center of power. By analyzing these archival and affective histories together, Rajagopalan works to redefine the historic monument—far from a symbol of a specific past, the monument is shown in Building Histories to be a culturally mutable object with multiple stories to tell.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArchitecture - Political aspects - India - New Delhi. 0aArchitecturexPolitical aspectszIndiazNew Delhi. 0aIslamic architecturezIndiazNew Delhi. 7aARCHITECTURE / General.2bisacsh  aASI.  aArchaeological Survey of India.  aDelhi.  aJama Masjid.  aPurana Qila.  aQutb Minar.  aRasul Numa Dargah.  aRed Fort.  aarchitecture.  acolonial histories.  apreservation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022628347040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226331898423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226331898/original  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles